Writings.—If we except the youthiul but brilliant Dic· loyua and numerous speeches which the distinguished orator

doubtless published from timeto time, according to the prevailing custom, Tacitus's illustrious career as a writer begins with the Agricola, which appeared shortly after the death oi Nerva (J an. 27, 98 nn), although the entire work, with the exceptiones the prooemium (1-3) and one passage at the close,s may well have been composed immediately after the death oi Domitian.

In the same year there followed the Germanic, the date being fixed by oh. 37, 5 ff. oi that work.

The Historias, announced as in contemplation in the Apri- eolo (ch. 3, 28-30), appeared between 105-109. They com· prised the story of the reigns oi Galba, Otho, Vitellius, Vespasian, Titus, and Domitian, but only the first four books and a fragment of the fifth, dealing with the year 69-7 0, have survived.

The Annulo began with the death of Augustus, and con- cluded with the assassination oi Nero in 68 an. Only bks. I.-IV., portions of V. and VI, and bks. XI.-XVI. are preserved, the entire narrative of the reign oi Caligula, the beginning of that of Claudius, and the end of Nero's being lost.
